    <h1>CON&#xAD;CERTS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200918/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-18"><time>2020-09-18</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE HAPPENINGS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Rus­sian Tra­di­tions: Sasha Farseev And Sasha Soup­tel</p>
    <p>Em­ploy­ing the ac­cor­dion and vi­o­lin, Sasha Farseev and Sasha Soup­tel team up to show­case Rus­sian tra­di­tional and modern mu­sic. From the jaunty Naughty Tunes to con­tem­po­rary num­bers such as Suites by Soviet com­poser V. Zolotaryov, each piece of mu­sic is ac­com­pa­nied by a story that not only ex­plains its artis­tic ori­gins, but also de­fines its spirit. Soup­tel per­formed as a soloist with var­i­ous renowned or­ches­tras and led the Moscow Sym­phony Orches­tra be­fore serv­ing as a con­cert­mas­ter of the Sin­ga­pore Sym­phony Orches­tra from 1993 to 2013. Farseev, an award-win­ning ac­cor­dion­ist, has per­formed in hun­dreds of con­certs in Rus­sia, Eu­rope and Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>WHERE: View it on­line at Es­planade Off­stage WHEN: Avail­able till Oct 7, noon AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>
    <p>INFO: es­planade.com</p>
    <p>Tra­di­tion­ally Speak­ing – Scot­tish Tra­di­tional Mu­sic</p>
    <p>Tra­di­tion­ally Speak­ing is an all-Sin­ga­porean trio con­sist­ing of Law Chi-Yan (Scot­tish small­pipes, whis­tles), Pamela Ng (bodhran, flute) and Bryan Leong (gui­tar, keys). Join them for an evening of tra­di­tional mu­sic from Scot­land’s west coast in a per­for­mance that fea­tures tunes from Gaelic waltzes to grace­ful strath­speys com­posed for Scot­tish step danc­ing.</p>
    <p>WHERE: View it on­line at Es­planade Off­stage WHEN: Avail­able till Oct 7, noon AD­MIS­SION: Free</p>
    <p>INFO: es­planade.com</p>
    <p>Con­cor­dia Quar­tet – Back On Stage</p>
    <p>Con­cor­dia Quar­tet con­tinue their cel­e­bra­tion of the 250th an­niver­sary of Beethoven’s birth with his String Quar­tet No. 4. Also on the pro­gramme are the Diver­ti­mento In F Ma­jor by Mozart and the much-loved third move­ment from Borodin’s String Quar­tet No. 2. The evening of quar­tet mu­sic will be live-streamed from the Ngee Ann Kongsi The­atre @ Wild Rice. WHERE: View the live stream on YouTube WHEN: Tomorrow, 8pm INFO: bit.ly/3iGj17O</p>


